<heading id="D0D4327CBF01FF23FC30FC65FAEEFC73" box="[926,1342,924,948]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" reason="5">
ARANEOIDEA AND 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FBDFFC65FAEEFC73" box="[1137,1342,924,948]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">TETRAGNATHIDAE</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C339D69BBF01FF23FC94FC3CFADDF9BE" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9C8510BF01FF23FC94FC3CFADDF9BE" blockId="3.[826,1442,965,1662]" pageId="3" pageNumber="288">
In this analysis 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FBB8FC3CFB16FC1B" box="[1046,1222,965,987]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tetragnathidae</taxonomicName>
is sister to the ‘reduced piriform clade’ (RPC) 
<emphasis id="B9575902BF01FF23FB02FC1DFB3BFC39" box="[1196,1259,996,1017]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="288">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB2F8E1BF01FF23FB59FC1AFC54FBD8" author="Griswold CE &amp; Coddington JA &amp; Hormiga G &amp; Scharff N" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" pagination="1 - 99" refId="ref29414" refString="Griswold CE, Coddington JA, Hormiga G, Scharff N. 1998. Phylogeny of the orb-web building spiders (Araneae, Orbiculariae: Deinopoidea, Araneoidea). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 123: 1 - 99." type="journal article" year="1998">
Griswold 
<emphasis id="B9575902BF01FF23FAC4FC1DFA4BFC38" box="[1386,1435,995,1017]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="288">et al</emphasis>
. (1998)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FC3BFBFBFB95FBD8" box="[917,1093,1026,1048]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tetragnathidae</taxonomicName>
plus the RPC are sister to 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FC94FBD8FC60FBF7" box="[826,944,1057,1079]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Araneidae</taxonomicName>
and all these taxa conform to Araneoidea. The phylogenetic relationships within the RPC are beyond the scope of this paper and were studied in some detail by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB2F8E1BF01FF23FC48FB84FB0CFB53" author="Griswold CE &amp; Coddington JA &amp; Hormiga G &amp; Scharff N" box="[998,1244,1149,1171]" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" pagination="1 - 99" refId="ref29414" refString="Griswold CE, Coddington JA, Hormiga G, Scharff N. 1998. Phylogeny of the orb-web building spiders (Araneae, Orbiculariae: Deinopoidea, Araneoidea). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 123: 1 - 99." type="journal article" year="1998">
Griswold 
<emphasis id="B9575902BF01FF23FBFAFB84FB55FB52" box="[1108,1157,1149,1170]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="288">et al</emphasis>
. (1998)
</bibRefCitation>
. Two synapomorphies support the monophyly of the RPC: short bases of the piriform spigots (7-1) and the three-dimensional web structure (105-1). 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FB94FB20FB3AFB2F" box="[1082,1258,1241,1263]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tetragnathidae</taxonomicName>
and the spiders of the RPC share three synapomorphies: the loss of the aciniform anterior brush of the PMS (9-1), the nonsticky silk spiral and the first sticky silk in contact (102-1), and the use of the iL1 (first leg facing the hub) to measure where to attach the sticky silk spiral (103-1). Two synapomorphies support the monophyly of 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FCFBFA56FC1EFA05" box="[853,974,1455,1477]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Araneidae</taxonomicName>
: the grooved booklung cover cuticle (3-1), and the presence of a radix in the embolic division (69-1). The booklung cover cuticle is also grooved in 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FC94F9F2FC6AF9E1" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1894" box="[826,954,1547,1569]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nephilinae">Nephilinae</taxonomicName>
, except 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FBBAF9F2FADFF9E1" authority="Simon, 1889" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1889" box="[1044,1295,1547,1569]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Clitaetra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9575902BF01FF23FBBAF9F2FBAAF9E0" box="[1044,1146,1547,1568]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="288">Clitaetra</emphasis>
Simon, 1889
</taxonomicName>
, and in 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FAC7F9F5FA72F9E1" box="[1385,1442,1548,1569]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Meta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9575902BF01FF23FAC7F9F5FA72F9E1" box="[1385,1442,1548,1569]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="288">Meta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within the ‘metines 
<emphasis id="B9575902BF01FF23FB8BF9D2FB96F980" box="[1061,1094,1579,1600]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="288">s.s.</emphasis>
’ clade. The phylogenetic relationships of 
<taxonomicName id="4C23FE93BF01FF23FC7FF9B0FB97F99F" box="[977,1095,1609,1631]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Araneidae</taxonomicName>
have been studied in detail elsewhere (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB2F8E1BF01FF23FC15F99EFAD0F9BE" author="Scharff N &amp; Coddington JA" box="[955,1280,1639,1662]" pageId="3" pageNumber="288" pagination="355 - 434" refId="ref30394" refString="Scharff N, Coddington JA. 1997. A phylogenetic analysis of the orb-weaving spider family Araneidae (Arachnida, Araneae). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 120: 355 - 434." type="journal article" year="1997">Scharff &amp; Coddington, 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
